But each time, a central authority control and process exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both trustees of the ledger, auditors, issuers of money, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network?
Each transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses as an e -mail.
Except that a user can select a different address for each payment, ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically by a system of double encryption key.
The network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins exchanged actually exist in the book of public accounts, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write the new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner of which, a kind of provisional central banker will have the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a file hash stage, that is to say processing of a large file into a shorter, unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "are" the new transaction and it add a number before "chop" all.
The goal is to find the number that gives a special footprint (many zeros).
Once this number is reached, the other nodes easily verify that this is correct.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the footprint.
